### Description

My use case is when using pagination in a way it appends the next page array to the current array (like an infinite scroll) instead of just navigating between pages,  I need a way to get the previous value (array of products, for example) and be able to concatenate the new array of products (next page) to that previous value.

This is how I do it without the resource API (using effect):

```typescript
  constructor() {
    effect(() => {
      this.#productsService
        .getProducts(this.page())
        .pipe(takeUntilDestroyed(this.#destroyRef))
        .subscribe((products) =>
          this.page() === 1
            ? this.products.set(products)
            : this.products.update((current) => current.concat(products))
        );
    });
  }
```

### Proposed solution

Add an update value function to the ResourceOptions and RxResourceOptions that receives the previous value, the current value and the request object.

```typescript
  productsResource = rxResource<Product[], number>({
    request: () => this.page(),
    loader: ({ request: page }) => this.#productsService.getProducts(page),
    updateValue: (prev, current, {request:page}) => page === 1 ? current : prev.concat(current),
  });
```

I don't know if there's a (simple and elegant) way of doing this using the resource API. I can't use scan in the observable because it only gets the first emitted value and restarts the observable every time.

By default the function will just return the current value.

### Alternatives considered

I don't know how to do this in a more efficient way while using the resource API to load the data. Maybe it's not the way it's intended to be used.

